{"parse":{"title":"Xylospongium","pageid":38547758,"revid":846591836,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Xylospongium.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ed/Xylospongium.jpg/220px-Xylospongium.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"128\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ed/Xylospongium.jpg/330px-Xylospongium.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ed/Xylospongium.jpg/440px-Xylospongium.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"3438\" data-file-height=\"2008\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Xylospongium.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>A replica xylospongium (sponge on a stick)</div></div></div>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Ostia-Toilets.JPG\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/44/Ostia-Toilets.JPG/220px-Ostia-Toilets.JPG\" width=\"220\" height=\"165\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/44/Ostia-Toilets.JPG/330px-Ostia-Toilets.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/44/Ostia-Toilets.JPG/440px-Ostia-Toilets.JPG 2x\" data-file-width=\"1024\" data-file-height=\"768\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Ostia-Toilets.JPG\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Ancient Roman latrines in Ostia Antica</div></div></div>\n<p>The <b>xylospongium</b> (greek) or <b>tersorium</b> (roman), also known as <i>sponge on a stick</i>, was a <a href=\"/wiki/Hygienic\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Hygienic\">hygienic</a> utensil used by <a href=\"/wiki/Ancient_Roman\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Ancient Roman\">ancient Romans</a> to wipe their buttocks after <a href=\"/wiki/Defecating\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Defecating\">defecating</a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> consisting of a wooden stick (<a href=\"/wiki/Ancient_Greek\" title=\"Ancient Greek\">Greek</a>: \u03be\u03cd\u03bb\u03bf\u03bd, <i>Xylon</i>) with a <a href=\"/wiki/Sea_sponge\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Sea sponge\">sea sponge</a> (Greek: \u03a3\u03c0\u03cc\u03b3\u03b3\u03bf\u03c2, <i>Spongos</i>) fixed at one end.\n</p><p>The tersorium was shared by people using public latrines. To clean the sponge, they simply washed it in a bucket with water and salt or vinegar.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> This became a breeding ground for bacteria, causing the spread of disease in the latrine.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In the <a href=\"/wiki/Classical_antiquity\" title=\"Classical antiquity\">classical antiquity</a> a <i>xylospongium</i> might be used in the same way as we use a <a href=\"/wiki/Toilet_brush\" title=\"Toilet brush\">toilet brush</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In the <i><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Baths_of_the_seven_sages&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Baths of the seven sages (page does not exist)\">baths of the seven sages</a></i> in <a href=\"/wiki/Ostia_(Rome)\" title=\"Ostia (Rome)\">Ostia</a>, a <a href=\"/wiki/Fresco\" title=\"Fresco\">fresco</a> from the 2nd century contains the Inscription <i>(u)taris xylosphongio</i><sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> which is the first known mention of the term.\nAlso in the early second century a papyrus letter of <a href=\"/wiki/Claudius_Terentianus\" title=\"Claudius Terentianus\">Claudius Terentianus</a> to his father <a href=\"/wiki/Claudius_Tiberianus\" title=\"Claudius Tiberianus\">Claudius Tiberianus</a> uses the term <i>xylospongium</i> in a phrase.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In the middle of the first century <a href=\"/wiki/Seneca_the_Younger\" title=\"Seneca the Younger\">Seneca</a> reported that a Germanic gladiator had committed suicide with a sponge on a stick. The German hid himself in the latrine of an amphitheater and pushed the wooden stick into his gullet and choked to death.<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Xylospongium&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Mirsky, Steve. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/toilet-tissue-anthropologists-uncover-all-the-ways-weve-wiped/\">\"Getting to the Bottom\"</a>. <i>Scientific American</i>. <b>308</b> (3): 85\u201385. <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//doi.org/10.1038/scientificamerican0313-85\">10.1038/scientificamerican0313-85</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Scientific+American&amp;rft.atitle=Getting+to+the+Bottom&amp;rft.volume=308&amp;rft.issue=3&amp;rft.pages=85-85&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1038%2Fscientificamerican0313-85&amp;rft.aulast=Mirsky&amp;